Here are the Top 5 reasons why this is one of my proudest works. 

1. I get to pay homage to all the artists that have influenced and impacted not only me but the art of MCing in some way on a track. 

2. The fact that The Godfather of Hip-Hop himself @officialdjkoolherc graced us with his presence for the video. 

3. With things not panning out the way I expected with my major label debut, the making of this song and the project it’s from (The Emcee’s Properganda) allowed me a chance to go back to the essence of it all. 

4. I got to link up with a young @goldenchildgs. 

5. With Hip-Hop turning 50 this year, this track means even that much more to me as a way to reflect on how far the music and culture itself has come. 

With that said, here’s my Top 5 in alphabetical order. 

Biggie 
Eminem 
Jay-z
LL Cool J
Nas

Who’s your Top 5?

#HipHop50 #Top5

I was 18. Aside from battling all around my neighborhood of North Miami Beach and pretty much anywhere I could find someone to battle, I had also participated in all the notable competitions and tournaments I could find, big and small. I was extra hype to qualify for Grab The Mic 2000 for a few reasons. I knew J Pure (RIP) one of my hugest freestyling influences at the time was in the battle. And also, RK, another staple in the scene at the time was in it as well. RK just came back from winning the Blaze Battle in Orlando, where he would go on to battle Eyedea (RIP) on the HBO special. From a credibility standpoint, I knew winning this would be a great level-up for me. This was also the first tournament I was in that had a large cash prize. 1,000 of them thangs to be exact. 🤑 Again, this is 2000 and I’m a high school senior. That might as well have been a million bucks. I was coasting my way through all my opponents and this was the last round. Won’t spoil it but let’s just say.. Drinks on me! 🤣🤯 

Fun fact. This clip is actually from a DVD I dropped called #KnowingIsHalfTheBattle around 2006. Pretty much the story of how I started battling in Miami and ended up on 106. #TheChineseKidThatRaps

During my heyday in the battlerap world, I’ve probably been called Data from the Goonies or Shortround from Indiana Jones in some form or fashion as many times as the child actor who portrayed these iconic roles himself. Ironically, not only did I never feel the sting in these references as much as my opponents would have hoped for, more often than not, I’d fully embrace being momentarily casted as these characters and use it to my advantage. “Yeah I’m Shortround when I step in the room, battling me, you just entered the Temple of Doom.” And the crowd would go nuts. In fact, the art of the racial rebuttal sort of became my forte. Let the Data show, time after time, my opponents would fall right into the “booty traps”. 😅

I read an AP news article where Ke says that if he were offered the role of Waymond 10 years ago, he doesn’t think he could have played it. “Everything had to happen the way it did. It’s fate.” Turning 40 last year and reflecting on all the various waves of my own career journey, this sentiment strikes every single chord possible in my heart and mind. Similarly, I can say that watching Ke’s well deserved resurrgence into the spotlight may not have the same effect it’s currently having on me if this were 10 years ago. 

Ke adamantly emphasized in his Oscar speech the importance of his wife’s unwavering support and encouragement during the stagnant decades that followed his initial breakout years, simply stating, “Your time will come.” It’s safe to say her words were not only accurate, but will Echo for quite some time to come. (See what I did there!) 🥰

On screen, Shortround won audiences over with his loyalty. Data captured hearts with his innocence. Waymond stunned us with both his charm and humility. Off screen, Ke’s real life character and resilient spirit shows us all that much like Goonies, dreams must never say die! 

Congrats @kehuyquan! I look forward to shaking your hand one day and thanking you in person for how your experience has impacted me personally.

In 2017, I joined the Rap of China competition with two clear goals. One, I wanted to learn more about Chinese Hip-Hop. Two, after over two decades of rhyming primarily in English, and then later on Cantonese, I wanted to take on a new challenge: kickin’ some Mandarin bars. Saying it was a challenge is probably an understatement considering I went into the show with a total of probably 10-15 words in my Mandarin vocab. As the show progressed, I (slowly but surely) progressed in my Mandarin speaking and rhyming abilities. I made it through about 3/4th show, until I eventually got eliminated, which happened to be the best outcome because it showed that the spirit of the competition was authentic. Even though “MC Jin” was no longer in the running, the spirit of “HipHopMan”, which was an identity I introduced at the start of the show, remained imprinted in the hearts and minds of many viewers. Excited to be back six years later. This time with new goals, new challenges, but the same spirit. Most important of all, with a few more words in my Mandarin vocab.

In 2017, I participated in the Rap of China show as a contestant under the identity of HipHopMan. The name itself stems from me overhearing my then 5 year old @chancetheson one day. “Some of my friends like Spider-Man, some like Iron Man, I like my daddy HipHopMan.” Like every superhero, HipHopMan has his own origin story. He’s been rapping all his life in English and now wants to challenge himself by rapping in Mandarin, which he barely spoke. Along the way I revealed my true identity, although many had a hunch of who I was under the mask. When I was invited back to perform for the finale episode, it was only fitting to do my first ever all Mandarin track, HipHopMan. Essentially, this song is a origin story itself.  The origins of HipHop and how it forever changed the life of a 13 year old Chinese kid. Fast forward to 2023. I turned 40 last year. HipHop turns 50 this year. Honored to once again bring this special track back to the Rap of China stage. This is dedicated to all the HipHopMans around the world. HipHop Family Forever. 🫡❤️#RapOfChina2023 #HipHop50

「古灵靖怪」(pronounced gǔ líng jìng guài), is a spin on a classic Chinese idiom that essentially means “zany or off the wall”. I replaced one of the words with my name, which happens to have the same sound. In other words, you can call it “The Zany Off the Wall Jin Show”. When the opportunity to launch my own tour came knocking on my door, I knew I wanted to do something outside of the conventional concert. Something that could showcase the multiple facets of “MC Jin”. A bit of musical theater, a bit of sketch comedy and a ton of “What the heck”?! It’s a format that I’ve never done before. It was surreal to watch it all come to life last night in Guangzhou! I couldn’t have kicked off the tour with a better special guest than @lam_fung_official who’s always been a crowd favorite whether on the singing or acting tip for decades! I would say by age 15, I knew definitively that I only had one life-path ahead of me. That path included me on stage, a mic in hand and a DJ on the ones and twos. What I did NOT foresee was that the stage would be hovering over a jam packed waterpark pool, with massive water+fire cannons blasting off rounds simultaneously as I’m rhyming (looking like a scene straight out of Avatar the last Airbender), random water jetpack flyers soaring around and last but certainly not least, two 10 ft. tall fully armed, robot warriors doing the two-step behind me. And yet here we are. 🤷🏻‍♂️🤣🎤🤪

At 15, I fell in love with you even though no one thought we had a future together.

At 19, we formally tied the knot in front of millions on TV. 

At 24, things got rocky and we had to take our relationship back to it’s essence.

At 41, you’ve graciously been by my side for 2/3 of my life, as I’ve evolved as an MC, and grown from a boy to a man. 

Together, we’ve tasted sweet success and swallowed the bitterness of setbacks. In the end, I’m humbled to say that as I set out to make my mark, my passion for the craft also allowed me to make history. This is only made possible by all those who paved the way before me. Salute to all of you. 🫡💐

Story time…

Around 2013 I happened to be performing in a showcase at South by Southwest. During one of my free days, I found myself roaming around one of the primary event halls just exploring. Serendipitously, I stumbled into one of the huge conference rooms featuring a fireside chat with none other than “Mr. We used to be number 10, now we permanent at 1” himself! Having not crossed paths in a decade, I sat down quietly in the last row, ears and eyes wide open soaking up every bit of the convo happening on stage. Towards the end, a mic was set up off stage, in the center of the room for a general Q&A session. Naturally, a line of people who wanted to pose a question for Mr. Jean rapidly formed. Naturally, I found myself standing in the back of the line, eager to ask my million dollar question. And when my turn came up, I did. “Yo what’s up Clef, huge fan here. What do you think of that Chinese kid from back in the days that was battling on 106 and Park?” 😏🫣🤭 It was dark in the room, so I think it took a quick moment for him to register the voice and who was asking this, but once he connected the dots… that’s when the magic happened. 🎤🔥

Bringing this back today to celebrate and honor @wyclefjean. Happy Born Day King! So much love and appreciation for you, your art and your heart. 💐💯❤️

Year: 2000. Location: Miami. Setting: Prom Night. The lack of enthusiasm on our face could be because it’s been a whole hour and the DJ hasn’t played a single Mobb Deep joint. Don’t get me wrong. I’m not mad at all that the entire Slip N Slide catalogue has gotten heavy rotation. Shoot, I wouldn’t even mind “Taking it to the house” 20 more times. But man, even the first 22 seconds of Drop A Gem On ‘Em would’ve been enough to hold us over for the rest of the night. The odds of a Wu set was also unlikely, but man, if Triumph came on? Oh forget about it. I would’ve been so hyped. That red bow tie would’ve been ripped off and flung into the punch bowl before Deck’s verse even started. For the sake of my outfit, maybe it’s a good thing we just vibed out to the sounds of the Baddest B%^*. 🤣🤭 Did you go to your prom? What year? What song(s) were you waiting for the DJ to drop? 🤷🏻‍♂️🤷🏻‍♂️🤷🏻‍♂️
